A: The StringTokenizer class in Java is designed to tokenize strings, i.e., break them up into smaller parts. It does this by splitting the string wherever it encounters the delimiter you've specified.
The StringTokenizer.nextToken() method returns the next token from the string. If the delimiter is an empty string, it treats consecutive delimiters as a single delimiter. This is why it's skipping over empty fields.
If you want to read in empty fields, you should use a different class, such as String.split() or Scanner, which can handle this case.
Here's an example using String.split():
String strLine = "one->two->->three";
String[] tokens = strLine.split("->");
for (String token : tokens) {
    System.out.println(token);
}

This will output:
one
two

three

This will read in empty fields as well.

